Good, I've added explicit dimensions to the Canvas container. But wait, I should also check if the issue is that the Scene component is still using static imports from R3F, which might be causing the ReactCurrentOwner error to still occur, just silently.

Let me check if we need to also make the imports within Scene.tsx dynamic. Actually, looking at it again, the problem is that Scene.tsx has:

```javascript
import { OrbitControls, Stars, Float, PerspectiveCamera } from '@react-three/drei';
import { EffectComposer, Bloom } from '@react-three/postprocessing';
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber';
```

These are static imports at the top level. Even though Scene.tsx is being dynamically imported, these top-level imports execute when the module is evaluated, which happens during the build phase for Next.js.

The solution is to make these imports dynamic as well, or to lazy load the entire component tree. Let me try a different approach - lazy load the R3F components within Scene.tsx.

